resources.string:
ADVANCED ENCRYPTION STANDARD

The apps function implements the encryption algorithm for images using AES (Advanced Encryption Standard). This algorithm uses a symmetric key and applies the AES standard to ensure the security of the image during transmission or storage. 

 General process:
- Creating and extracting the master key from the app for use as the basis for creating the encryption key;
 - Applying the SHA hash function to the master key to obtain a fixed-length key;
Using the key to initialize the cipher object using the AES algorithm;
- Encrypting data from the source stream using AES;
- Encrypted data is written to the output file; 
- Closing the streams.

Hash function SHA (Secure Hash Algorithm). Here are some key characteristics:
- Hash length. SHA produces a hash value of fixed length (for security purposes, the length of the hash value is not disclosed).
- Collision resistance. SHA provides a high level of collision resistance. Collisions occur when two different input messages generate the same hash value. For SHA, collisions may be theoretically possible, but their occurrence requires a huge amount of computational resources.
- The apps master key is used as the basis for creating the encryption key. To bring the master key to a fixed length, SHA is applied. This ensures that regardless of the length of the original master key, the result will be a hash of fixed length that can then be used as the encryption key.
